NDE is in the process of reviewing/revising the English/Language Arts Standards. See the information below that includes a link to a public survey that can be filled out by anyone interested in providing input!

-----

The Nebraska State Board of Education approves content area standards in all content areas. “Nebraska’s College and Career Ready Standards for English Language Arts” were approved in 2014 and pursuant to state statute, now require revision. An important part of this process is gathering broad feedback on the content and rigor of the current ELA standards. The revision committee will consider the information collected from the 2021 Nebraska English Language Arts Public Input Survey when revising the current standards.

https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_41Iu9hTERmyspYV

post_text:
We are very excited to get the kids back in the building, but we want to remind everyone that there are three simple things everyone can do to keep us in school, keep our activities on schedule, and keep everyone healthy.

1. Social Distance (stay at least 6 feet apart whenever possible).
2. Wash hands regularly (and use hand sanitizer appropriately).
3. Wear a face covering (keeping Dress Code in mind!)

We ask that all students wear face coverings whenever tolerable. This will be especially for times when social distancing cannot be maintained (ie: the bus, moving in the hallways, assemblies, etc.). We will plan on allowing "mask breaks" in the classroom as much as possible.

Also, if your child has a water bottle, please have them bring it with as we will be encouraging the use of the water bottles instead of using the water fountains.

Please watch the following video with your child by Bring Up Nebraska to give them an idea on how they can help: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yyccC5DI_eg

post_text:
With the increase of cases that we are seeing our area at this time, we want all parents/students to strongly consider using face coverings when we get back to school. While we will not mandate them at this time, we will be review this on a daily basis.

We understand that wearing a face covering will not eliminate the chances of getting sick, but there is plenty of evidence that it will lower your risk. We also understand that there are situations where students will not be able to wear them.

At the same time, for those that can, wearing a mask will reduce our chances of having to quarantine a large portion of our students/staff in the event of a positive case. That will allow us to keep ourselves in school and will allow us to maintain face-to-face learning as long as possible.

Thanks

post_text:
After some consideration, we have decided to wait until Tuesday to get the high school started.

We will not have open houses for either the high school or elementary at this time. Here is the schedule for the week:

Monday - No school/teacher work day. Practices will be in Thedford at 4:15. This WILL include the Junior High sports as they were scheduled to start this day. No Board Meeting this night.

Tuesday - First day for 7-12. Students will be allowed to take laptops home but must fill out paperwork and return on Wednesday in order to keep taking them home.

Wednesday - First day for K-6 students. Regular Board Meeting at 7:00 pm

Thursday - K-12 in session

Friday - K-12 in session, 2:14 dismissal.

We are sorry for any inconvenience these changes have caused. Please let us know if you have any questions.

post_text:
From Mr Dahlberg:

We are very bummed that we could not have the kids in today. We were all looking forward to a new year and to get a great start.

The decision to delay the start was made due to the uncertainty that we have right now.

As of right now, we have two staff members that were considered in contact with the positive case. Both are quarantining and both have been tested (awaiting results).

If both are negative, we should be ready to roll on Monday with the 7-12 students.

If one, or both, are positive, we may need to make further adjustments to our starting plans. If either test positive, there is a chance more of our staff (and maybe some students) will need to quarantine.

While we do not want to cause any panic, we wanted to keep everyone as informed as possible. We WILL get the kids back into the building, but don’t feel it is best until there is less uncertainty in the risk of bringing them back.

Hopefully we will get through this relatively quick and can get the kids in the building as soon as possible.

Please don’t hesitate to contact me with any questions.

From Mr Dahlberg:

To clarify the information from last night. The WCDHD has stated that students wearing masks would not be required to quarantine unless they test positive.

Students that don’t wear masks run the risk of having to quarantine due to a classmate/staff member testing positive.

Any requirement for masks would be to try and prevent unnecessary quarantine of healthy students.

Also, there is the opportunity for parents to opt out of any potential requirement.

If you have questions, please let me know!

Participants included Winter Benscoter, Ariel Bryant, Jared Inman, Makayla Osienger, Maranda Osienger, Rhiannon Painter, Jakob Schaefer, Owen Blumenstock, Riggin Blumenstock, Aidan Bryant, Chris Eggert, Tyson Hickman, Mariah Osienger, Brayden Schaefer, Keghan Schaefer, and Brodie Stengel.

Rhiannon Painter was a State Officer this past year.

Great job SkillsUSA Kids!

For parents of students that qualify for free/reduced lunch:

You can apply for Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) through the Families First Coronavirus Act. Families that qualify for SNAP benefits will automatically receive these benefits.

If you do not qualify for SNAP, but do qualify for free or reduced lunch prices, you are still eligible to apply.

The FAQ can be found here: http://dhhs.ne.gov/Documents/COVID-19-Pandemic-EBT-FAQ.pdf

The application can be found here:
https://cip-dhhs.ne.gov/redcap/surveys/?s=DM3WNPMJN7

If you have any questions or need information (you will need your child's identification number), please contact the school.

PUBLIC NOTICE - THEDFORD SCHOOLS SURPLUS PROPERTY

Thedford Public School is accepting sealed bids for the sale and removal of the following surplus property:

Two (2) fuel oil tanks and concrete pads (must remove concrete pad along
with each tank).

One (1) Semi Trailer

All property will be sold “as is” and it will be the responsibility of the buyer to remove the items from school property. Interested buyers can set up an appointment to inspect the items by contacting Mr. Dahlberg at the school via email (blake.dahlberg@thedfordschools.org) or phone at 308-645-2614, extension 101.

All bids must be submitted to the Thedford Schools Office no later than June 15th at 4:00 p.m. Bids can be mailed to Thedford Schools, PO Box 248, Thedford, NE 69166 or can be dropped off at the school.

Please write “Sealed Bid for (item you are bidding on)” on the envelope before dropping off or mailing.

Bids will be opened at the regular board meeting on June 15th starting at 7:30 p.m. The Thedford Board of Education reserves the right to reject any and all bids.

NSAA Sport Physical Update:

Dear Parents - NSAA is making a ONE-YEAR exemption only to accept last years sport physicals as eligible for the upcoming 2020-21 school year (please read attachment for more information if you want). INCOMING FRESHMEN are the only ones exempt from this. Incoming freshmen will still need to complete the 5 page NSAA Physical Form. Mr.Dahlberg will have these physical forms ready to hand to you at checkout this week. There will be extra forms in the office during the summer. These forms cannot be dated prior to May 1, 2020 for incoming freshmen.

These must be completed before the student returns to school in the fall. Without this form, no student can participate in any NSAA school athletic/activities.

If there are any questions - please reach out to Bec Ray or Mr. Dahlberg for more information. Thank you

Registration forms are included for students going into grades 9-12 and we ask that they are returned as well.

Any students that have items in the locker rooms will need to clean them out when they check out.

Please let Mr. Dahlberg know if you have any questions!

Please see the information below from NDE. Anyone can fill out the survey to help provide them feedback!

-----

THE NEBRASKA DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
SEEKS FEEDBACK ON FEDERAL CARES ACT

The Nebraska Department of Education is seeking feedback to help school districts address immediate needs in response to the coronavirus pandemic.

The United States Congress passed the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, And Economic Security (CARES) Act, which includes one-time relief funding for local school districts, intended to address challenges of providing education during the COVID-19 pandemic.

The NDE is asking for responses through a short survey to understand local needs as well as potential investments and support. The survey is available in English and Spanish on the department’s website: https://nde.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_efislqh4QDEA1KZ.

Everyone is encouraged to fill out the survey by Monday, May 11, 2020.

post_text:
We will be extending our suspension of normal operations until April 30th. We will re-evaluate the situation as we get closer to that date.

The Board approved an amendment to their attendance policies through this time that define attendance as “the completion of educational goals provided to the students by the teachers”.

Please continue to work on the information provided by the teachers. 6-12 students should be checking their google classroom and emails daily. Elementary teachers have communication channels set up to help get information, lessons, and activities out to everyone in their classes.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact Mr. Dahlberg.

post_text:
All parents (from Mr. Dahlberg):

Please know that what has been posted today (suggested timeline) could be used as the minimum. We will certainly support your expectations of having the students work on things longer/more if needed (especially any additional reading, writing, or math practice you choose to have them do).

If you have any issues or concerns, please don't hesitate to contact me. As it is still the teacher's responsibility to continue to provide educational opportunities for the students, it is my responsibility to make sure the students are following the expectations and guidelines of the teachers and other adults involved in their education (ie: you!)

In other words, you have every right to send your kids to the principal's "office" during this time if they need it!

5th Grade Parents,

The following is from Mrs. Maseberg:

Suggested Possible Time Frame 5th Parents Might Want to Follow:

45 minutes per day - English/Language Arts
45 minutes per day - Math
15 minutes per day - Writing ---Journal Entries
30 minutes per day - Sci./Soc. Studies (alternating days )
Total 2 Hours and 15 minutes daily

New Packets with New Materials coming out every two weeks. Students can return completed work when they pick up new packet. Packets can be mailed out if necessary. Just let me know!

Students will be provided with both on and off-line learning activities. When on-line, students are encouraged to utilize IXL and Spelling City. Both of these are teacher-monitored sites checked daily by Mrs. Maseberg! (Spelling City login information coming in next packet)

Communication---Through email/text messages –contact information provided in initial packet sent home on March 18th

Just released by the NSAA: All NSAA activity practices and competitions are suspended through May 1st. These suspensions may be extended should the conditions warrant.

Member schools and student-participants are expected to adhere to the NSAA Constitution & Bylaws and activity manuals during this time.

The NSAA encourages all member schools to follow CDC, local, state and federal health department recommendations.

As more information becomes available, official updates will be posted on the NSAA website and the NSAA social media platforms.

Again...we greatly appreciate the extra work you are doing and the sacrifices you are making during this time! THANK YOU!

From the Leukemia and Lymphoma Society:

We at the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society want you to know that we are here to partner with you in any way we can during this time of uncertainty.

The health of our volunteers is of most importance to us and, like you, we are monitoring the Coronavirus situation closely and will continue to do what is best and safest for our staff and volunteers. Nonetheless, no matter what life throws its way, our Hero Squad is ready.

With so many school closures throughout the country and distance learning going into effect, we have developed a full set of resources of fun STEM activities students can complete at home. We’re all in this together!
Please feel free to share this link with your students and parents to download our STEM and SEL @ Home

Resources: https://llsdata.box.com/s/zybzgxkacyum481lbtr2ev1rzcg8scr5

Please stay home and practice good hygiene and social distancing. Thanks!

post_text:
SkillsUSA wants to thank all the teachers/staff/community members for their help in making our “Pie in the Face” fundraiser so successful. We were able to raise $264.70!

A GINORMOUS thanks to Mr. Cronk (1st place) and Mr. Dahlberg (2nd place) for “taking the pie in the face.”

And a HUUUGE THANKS to Mr. Chytka for being a good sport, and taking a pie in the face, too, when a community member offered to matched Mr. Dahlberg’s jar of money to make it a tie.

SkillsUSA gained two new junior high members, so some of the money will go to help pay for their competition expenses. The other money will be put towards competition supplies for the high school students.

Thanks again to everyone!

For this year’s Geography Bee, we registered the elementary and junior high as separate schools.

Therefore, we will have two school championship rounds.

4th-6th grade championship round will be next Wednesday, January 29th at 1:30 pm in the elementary library.

7th-8th grade championship round will be next Wednesday, January 29th at 2:30 pm in the high school library.

Each champion will get the opportunity to do the state qualifying test.

The 10 finalists for each championship round will be announced tomorrow morning!

post_text: Congratulations to the Aca Deca (Academic Decathalon) team! They earned 16 medals as a team, place 1st in the Super Quiz in our region, 3rd place overall in our region and 4th place in the state!! Our participants included Jakob Schaefer, Summar Schaefer, Tenley Rasmussen, Rhiannon Painter, Ariel Bryant, Cylee Jameson and Makayla Osienger. They will each receive a scholarship for their outstanding performance!
